‘E’, ‘END’, or ‘FINISH’ for end, ‘S’, ‘START’, or ‘BEGIN’ for start. Whether the elements should be aligned to the end or start within pa period. January 31st (‘END’) vs. January 1st (‘START’) for example.
‘Fiscal’ year with a century as a decimal number
‘Fiscal’ year without a century as a decimal number [00,99]
‘NaT’ will return NaT for an ambiguous time
‘NaT’ will return NaT where there are ambiguous times
‘NaT’ will return NaT where there are nonexistent times
‘S’, ‘E’. Can be aliased as case insensitive ‘Start’, ‘Finish’, ‘Begin’, ‘End’
‘a’: append, an existing file is opened for reading and writing, and if the file does not exist it is created.
‘all’ : All columns of the input will be included in the output.
‘all’ : If all values are NA, drop that row or column.
‘any’ : If any NA values are present, drop that row or column.
‘axes’ returns the matplotlib axes the boxplot is drawn on.
‘backfill’ / ‘bfill’: use NEXT valid observation to fill
‘backfill’ or ‘bfill’: use next valid observation to fill gap.
‘block’ tracks only the locations and sizes of blocks of data.

‘block’: Stores a block and block_length for each contiguous span of sparse values. This is best when sparse data tends to be clumped together, with large regions of fill-value values between sparse values.
‘both’ returns a namedtuple with the axes and dict.
‘broadcast’ : results will be broadcast to the original shape of the DataFrame, the original index and columns will be retained.
‘coerce’ will return NaT if the timestamp can not be converted into the specified timezone. Use nonexistent='NaT' instead.
‘coerce’ will return NaT if the timestamp can not be converted to the specified time zone. Use nonexistent='NaT' instead.
‘dict’ returns a dictionary whose values are the matplotlib Lines of the boxplot.
‘expand’ : list-like results will be turned into columns.
‘first’ : Drop duplicates except for the first occurrence.
‘first’ : Mark duplicates as True except for the first occurrence.
‘fixed’: Fixed format. Fast writing/reading. Not-appendable, nor searchable.
‘from_derivatives’: Refers to scipy.interpolate.BPoly.from_derivatives which replaces ‘piecewise_polynomial’ interpolation method in scipy 0.18.
‘ignore’ : suppress exceptions. On error return original object.
‘ignore’ : will ignore KeyError if keys listed in meta are not always present.
‘index’, ‘values’: use the actual numerical values of the index.
‘infer’ will attempt to infer fall dst-transition hours based on order
‘inside’: Only fill NaNs surrounded by valid values (interpolate).
‘integer’ keeps an array with all the locations of the data.
‘integer’ or ‘signed’: smallest signed int dtype (min.: np.int8)
‘integer’: uses an integer to store the location of each sparse value.
‘krogh’, ‘piecewise_polynomial’, ‘spline’, ‘pchip’, ‘akima’: Wrappers around the SciPy interpolation methods of similar names. See Notes.
‘last’ : Drop duplicates except for the last occurrence.
‘last’ : Mark duplicates as True except for the last occurrence.
‘left’ : the min value starts at the left of the cell.
‘linear’: Ignore the index and treat the values as equally spaced. This is the only method supported on MultiIndexes.
‘mid’ : the center of the cell is at (max-min)/2, or if values are all negative (positive) the zero is aligned at the right (left) of the cell.
‘mixed’ is the catchall for anything that is not otherwise specialized
‘multi’: Pass multiple values in a single INSERT clause.

‘nearest’, ‘zero’, ‘slinear’, ‘quadratic’, ‘cubic’, ‘spline’, ‘barycentric’, ‘polynomial’: Passed to scipy.interpolate.interp1d. These methods use the numerical values of the index. Both ‘polynomial’ and ‘spline’ require that you also specify an order (int), e.g. df.interpolate(method='polynomial', order=5).
‘nearest’: use nearest valid observation to fill gap.
‘outside’: Only fill NaNs outside valid values (extrapolate).
‘pad’ / ‘ffill’: propagate last valid observation forward to next valid
‘pad’ or ‘ffill’: use previous valid observation to fill gap (forward fill).
‘pad’: Fill in NaNs using existing values.
‘r+’: similar to ‘a’, but the file must already exist.
‘raise’ : will raise KeyError if keys listed in meta are not always present.
‘raise’ will raise a NonExistentTimeError if a timestamp is not
‘raise’ will raise a NonExistentTimeError if a timestamp is not valid in the specified time zone (e.g. due to a transition from or to DST time). Use nonexistent='raise' instead.
‘raise’ will raise an AmbiguousTimeError for an ambiguous time
‘raise’ will raise an AmbiguousTimeError if there are ambiguous times
‘raise’ will raise an NonExistentTimeError if there are nonexistent times
‘reduce’ : returns a Series if possible rather than expanding list-like results. This is the opposite of ‘expand’.
‘shift_backward’ will shift the nonexistent time backward to the closest existing time
‘shift_forward’ will shift the nonexistent time forward to the closest existing time
‘table’ : dict like {‘schema’: {schema}, ‘data’: {data}} describing the data, and the data component is like orient='records'.
‘table’: Table format. Write as a PyTables Table structure which may perform worse but allow more flexible operations like searching / selecting subsets of the data.
‘time’: Works on daily and higher resolution data to interpolate given length of interval.
‘w’: write, a new file is created (an existing file with the same name would be deleted).
‘zero’ : a value of zero is located at the center of the cell.
